content.text: Git Branch Merge
Change Platform:
What is Merging in Git?
Merging in Git means combining the changes from one branch into another.
content.html: Merging in Git means combining the changes from one branch into another.

content.text: This is how you bring your work together after working separately on different features or bug fixes.
content.html: This is how you bring your work together after working separately on different features or bug fixes.

content.text: Common git merge Options
Merging Branches ( git merge )
To combine the changes from one branch into another, use git merge .
content.html: To combine the changes from one branch into another, use git merge.

content.text: Usually, you first switch to the branch you want to merge into (often main or master ), then run the merge command with the branch name you want to combine in.
content.html: Usually, you first switch to the branch you want to merge into (often main or master), then run the merge command with the branch name you want to combine in.

content.text: First, we need to change to the master branch:
content.html: First, we need to change to the master branch:

content.code:
git
checkout master
Switched to branch 'master'
content.code_html:
git checkout master
Switched to branch 'master'

content.text: Now we merge the current branch (master) with emergency-fix:
content.html: Now we merge the current branch (master) with emergency-fix:

content.code:
git
merge emergency-fix
Updating 09f4acd..dfa79db
Fast-forward
index.html | 2 +-
1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)
content.code_html:
git merge emergency-fix
Updating 09f4acd..dfa79db
Fast-forward
 index.html | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

content.text: Since the emergency-fix branch came directly from master, and no other changes had been made to master while we were working, Git sees this as a continuation of master.
content.html: Since the emergency-fix branch came directly from master, and no other changes had been made to master while we were working, Git sees this as a continuation of master.

content.text: So it can "Fast-forward", just pointing both master and emergency-fix to the same commit.
content.html: So it can "Fast-forward", just pointing both master and emergency-fix to the same commit.

content.text: Best Practices for Merging Branches
Practical Examples
As master and emergency-fix are essentially the same now, we can delete emergency-fix, as it is no longer needed:
content.html: As master and emergency-fix are essentially the same now, we can delete emergency-fix, as it is no longer needed:

content.code:
git
branch -d emergency-fix
Deleted branch emergency-fix (was dfa79db).
content.code_html:
git branch -d emergency-fix
Deleted branch emergency-fix (was dfa79db).

content.text: Non-Fast-Forward Merge ( git merge --no-ff )
By default, if your branch can be merged with a fast-forward (no new commits on the base), Git just moves the branch pointer forward.
content.html: By default, if your branch can be merged with a fast-forward (no new commits on the base), Git just moves the branch pointer forward.

content.text: If you want to always create a merge commit (to keep history clearer), use git merge --no-ff branchname .
content.html: If you want to always create a merge commit (to keep history clearer), use git merge --no-ff branchname.

content.code:
git
merge --no-ff feature-branch
Merge made by the 'recursive' strategy.
index.html | 2 +-
1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)
content.code_html:
git merge --no-ff feature-branch
Merge made by the 'recursive' strategy.
 index.html | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

content.text: Squash Merge ( git merge --squash )
If you want to combine all the changes from a branch into a single commit (instead of keeping every commit), use git merge --squash branchname .
content.html: If you want to combine all the changes from a branch into a single commit (instead of keeping every commit), use git merge --squash branchname.

content.text: This is useful for cleaning up commit history before merging.
content.html: This is useful for cleaning up commit history before merging.

content.code:
git
merge --squash feature-branch
Squash commit -- not updating HEAD
Automatic merge went well; stopped before committing as requested
content.code_html:
git merge --squash feature-branch
Squash commit -- not updating HEAD
Automatic merge went well; stopped before committing as requested

content.text: Aborting a Merge ( git merge --abort )
If you run into trouble during a merge (like a conflict you don't want to resolve), you can cancel the merge and go back to how things were before with git merge --abort .
content.html: If you run into trouble during a merge (like a conflict you don't want to resolve), you can cancel the merge and go back to how things were before with git merge --abort.

content.code_html: git merge --abort

content.text: What is a Merge Conflict?
A merge conflict happens when changes in two branches touch the same part of a file and Git doesn't know which version to keep.
content.html: A merge conflict happens when changes in two branches touch the same part of a file and Git doesn't know which version to keep.

content.text: Think of it like two people editing the same sentence in a document in different ways—Git needs your help to decide which version to use.
content.html: Think of it like two people editing the same sentence in a document in different ways—Git needs your help to decide which version to use.

content.text: How to Resolve a Merge Conflict
Git will mark the conflict in your file.
content.html: Git will mark the conflict in your file.

content.text: You need to open the file, look for lines like <<< <<< < HEAD and == == == = , and decide what the final version should be.
content.html: You need to open the file, look for lines like <<<<<<< HEAD and =======, and decide what the final version should be.

content.text: Then, stage and commit your changes.
content.html: Then, stage and commit your changes.
